blog.name: pokegodsandmissingno
blog.title: P̵o̵K̸é̴G̸o̸D̷s̸ and Frightful Things to Come?
blog.description: There is a growing desire and expectation of humans here on Earth in making full contact with PoKéMoN who are still unknown. Back in 1995, when I saw my first UPM (Unindexed Pocket Monster), I found out very quickly that other people thought you were totally crazy if you said you saw such things. The world has changed quite a bit since then when I was a child. In fact, in late 1997, a poll taken in Kanto shows that for the first time ever, more than fifty percent of residents now believe in PokéGODS's. Since then, there have been polls that put the figure at over eighty percent or more.

summary: Let’s Talk About Pokemon - Frillish and Jellicent
title: Let’s Talk About Pokemon - Frillish and Jellicent
body:
592: Frillish

Yet another Pokemon that is a rather direct parallel, this time very clearly meant to be Unova’s “Tentacool,” as a sea-roaming jellyfish monster juxtaposed against the pair’s menace with looking prim and proper, well-dressed Pokemon, hence the name! They’re also our first ever Water/Ghost types, which is a type combination with such a ridiculous amount of potential to it, I’m surprised we don’t have another one yet. But these two are also some Pokemon with gender differences. Which is… sure. It kinda ties in with the royalty theme, the blue male being a prince becoming a king and the pink female being a princess evolving into a queen. I just wish maybe they picked different colors for it, or at least that they had a secondary color. Other than the lighter shade, they’re the same color all over.

Honestly the only problem I have with these two is not even necessarily their fault. But the fact that in the sea-surfing routes of the game, it’s all Frillish. Only Frillish. Just Frillish. That’s sadly the issue that comes with A. Making surfing an entirely optional part of the game and B. restricting the game to only the Pokemon they came up with for Gen 5. But even still, you could’ve come up with at least one other Pokemon to help not make it so the only thing inhabiting Unova’s oceans is just this jellyfish. The only reason they really didhn’t have more Pokemon to inhabit the seas in Black and White is because they wanted the type distribution to be as even as possible, and didn’t want Water type to overtake the Unovadex like it does for almost every other Generation.

Personal Score: 7/10

They aight for spooky jellies.

593: Jellicent

These two jelly-monsters may look goofy at first, especially with the male counterpart having a likeness to the Pringles Guy. But they look a little more sinister in appearance once you realize they got something of a fierce, blank stare. Which is no accident, seeing how the Pokedex goes on about how much this Pokemon make a hobby out of sinking ships and dragging their crews down to the bottom of the ocean where it’ll eat them. You’d almost maybe forget this line is Ghost type, but then it pulls something spooky like that. Yikes.

Personal Score: 7/10

A just as fine jelly.

Overall:

I feel like I like them in flavor more than I like their designs, but still. Suitably creepy.

[Archive]

summary: 31 Day Pokemon Challenge: Day 4 - Favorite Ghost Type: Mimikyu! I’m a really big fan of Pokemon variations, so I decided to try...
caption:
31 Day Pokemon Challenge:
Day 4 - Favorite Ghost Type: Mimikyu!

I’m a really big fan of Pokemon variations, so I decided to try my hand at one this time! I know Mimikyu is a big favorite with a lot of folks so I wanted to take a stab at something different. Maybe Mimikyu couldn’t find the things he needed to make a Pikachu disguise, but he had a black marker, some white cloth, tape, a cotton ball, and a leaf! I think he did a really good job!!
